Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards

node.text:
The jet-black home in Australia keeps its cool in more ways than one. Designed by Melbourne-based firm @editionoffice for a client dreaming of a peaceful retreat, the structure shows tranquility done right. “Discussions with the client focused upon providing a home as sanctuary—an elemental respite from a high-pressure professional life,” say the architects. Using a material palette of black wood and darkly pigmented concrete, the home wraps around a two-story opening that spotlights a verdant courtyard of ferns. On its east side—looking out at never-ending landscapes—the home holds two small bedrooms and a bathroom, along with a larger en suite with a private terrace. A narrow subterranean pool runs through the home, reflecting the horizon, and aims to resemble a natural swimming hole. Not only is the home an exquisite example of minimal design with a big impact, it’s also extremely functional in its setting. The house solely relies on cross ventilation, cooling by the pool before flowing up through the fern garden. To see more of the Federal House, hit the link in bio.
–

Blink and you might miss the subtle, upcycled beauty of this London flat. Alessia Mosci—creative director and co-owner of architecture and interiors practice @mwaiarchitects—had a guiding principle while heading into her remodel: resourceful constraint. “There is a tendency to just take everything out and start fresh,” Alessia says. “But we tried to work with the building whilst making the changes we wanted.” The canvas Alessia chose for her project was a 1903 Edwardian terrace building, converted into an apartment in the ‘70s, that yielded plenty of reusable materials and a few surprises. While exploring the space, the designer found a sealed-off loft/storage area upstairs, which she converted into an en suite. She also had the original floorboards removed, restored, and reinstalled under a rebuilt roof that now features generous skylights. Even the marble in the kitchen—left over from a past client—speaks to Alessia’s adaptation to preexisting materials. “It’s good to experiment,” says Alessia, reflecting on her finished home. “And to follow your instincts.” Take the full tour of her resourceful renovation, aptly named an Upcycled Project, when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

Once the sun goes down, this prefab home does a pretty neat trick. The team over at Rotterdam-based @orangearchitectsnl designed the roughly 970-square-foot space with a focus on social spaces, but the home’s true glory lies in its flexibility. By day, the house flexes it’s indoor/outdoor design through floor-to-ceiling windows and doors that look out to the bucolic setting of Texel, an island in the Netherlands. To maintain privacy once the sun falls, the owners can turn wooden panels on the first level 90 degrees to transform the living space into a private room for sleeping. The library also becomes a full-size bedroom, while the hidden shower and sink convert into an en suite bathroom. More than just a novelty, the innovative design continues to delight the homeowners. "It’s nice to see that Holiday Home—as compact as it is—feels comfortable and familiar to our client but also continues to surprise, inspire, and enchant them every day," shares Patrick Meijers, one of the firm’s partners. After five years in a quaint bungalow-style home, one young family had outgrown their footprint and were ready for an upgrade. For their Hermosa Beach renovation, Mardi and Anton Watts turned to @ras_a.studio, who, after a closer look, determined a reno on the tight lot wasn’t going to cut it. The firm instead designed this new two-story home, an airy stack of wood-slatted boxes, complementing both the area’s low-slung midcentury bungalows and its taller, more recent developments. The challenge laid in making the most square footage while meeting the city’s car-conscious zoning requirements. “How do we get enough space on the ground floor when Hermosa Beach dictates you need a two-car garage,” principal architect Robert Sweet recalls thinking. With a blessing from the city planning department, a mechanical lift that stacks one car atop the other was installed, reserving more square footage for the living areas. Despite its tiny footprint, Olive—an aptly named green houseboat—is fully equipped for a modern lifestyle. The 59-foot floating abode was designed in 2019 by its architect owners, and currently sits on Regents Canal in London. While extremely adorable, the home’s design is equally practical. They’re not wrong: past the sofa and two-seater dining table is a relatively large kitchen with oak-faced cabinets, along with a counter-to-ceiling backsplash that adds a sense of openness to the space. The opposite side of the boat holds the bedroom, along with a bathroom complete with an eco-friendly composting toilet. There’s even a charming outdoor seating area on the bow that extends a warm welcome through glass doors. Best of all, the houseboat is looking for new owners. When the architects at ATOMAA first approached this crumbling home in the Italian Alps, it was in pretty rough shape. But its agrarian heritage and abundance of reusable materials were undeniable, guiding a contemporary renovation that honors the past. The 1,530-square-foot home—dubbed House Cinsc—carefully balances authenticity with modern intervention, making it one family’s perfect retreat amid the towering peaks of Varzo, Italy. With the help of local artisans, Milan-based @atomaa.eu restored the exterior using stones from the original structure. The rugged shell now houses an unadorned yet welcoming space from which to observe the surrounding landscape. Inside, an entirely wooden core traces the shape of the stone exterior and lends the home warmth within “a context strongly characterized by stone,” as the ATOMAA team describes it. Just as intended, the restored home is rigorous and minimal, yet comfortably rustic. Perhaps more importantly, its neighboring rock formations and idyllic pastures remain untouched. Following a fire that destroyed its rear half, a home in Melbourne gets a serene addition that honors what stood before. "We wanted to preserve as much of the existing home as we could”, says Benjamin Shields, founder of architecture studio @dreamer.lab. The client, a nurse living in the Ascot Vale neighborhood, had requested a “nature-filled retreat capable of hosting large gatherings of extended family and friends, while still providing moments of restorative seclusion,” Shields remembers. As it was, the home was poorly insulated, didn’t connect to the backyard, and had dark interiors. The new rear addition—which features a kitchen and living and dining areas on the ground level, along with a primary bedroom on the first floor—now overlooks the backyard and a strategically placed courtyard, maintaining privacy from nearby neighbors. To preserve the heritage elements of the building, Shields left a section of the wall in the courtyard as a seat, and recycled the bricks for use in the paving, among other design considerations. A fully native green roof now leads off the primary bedroom to create a private terrace planted with a grassy flower garden. "[It’s] my favorite part of the project," says Shields. "It’s a very special place—it’s lush, quiet, and there’s a view over the native plants to the neighboring roofs. The client is also really starting to make the project her own through planting—we love it when we visit!” Take a walk through the home and its remarkable new addition at the link in bio.

It is perhaps misleading to call these three structures a summer house. But measuring 890 square feet altogether, referring to them as a set of summer houses would imply something grander than a modest trio of cabins tucked into a defunct granite quarry. The cluster began as a single “little box” on the island of Vinalhaven, Maine, that owners Nick and Nadja van Praag purchased after patiently waiting for something to crop up. Over the years, they’d make interior renovations with local builder, caretaker, and lifelong island resident Matt Conway. Later, after purchasing the adjacent lot where a mobile home stood, they expanded with an entirely new plan: @go_logic architectural designer Riley Pratt borrowed the idea from @alvaraalto sketches depicting a “peeled apart” summer cabin, in which interconnected volumes surround a central courtyard. The resulting trio of autonomous bedroom cabins is constructed with cross-laminated timber panels, and finished by Conway’s crew with mitered white pine. In time they’ll turn hoary, matching both the granite landscape and the local cottage vernacular. “The most amazing thing is the way Riley sited the place,” Nick says. “By raising and angling the buildings, it embraces the landscape and the ocean in a way that I could not have imagined.” Try Dwell+ at the link in bio for more on how the van Praag’s brought a Finnish design concept to the island of Vinalhaven.

After a renovation, this 1955 home in Portland now boasts fresh interiors and a covered patio for lounging in every season, rain or shine. The first thing that architect Risa Boyer of @risaboyerarchitecture noticed upon walking through the home pre-reno wasn’t the interiors. “What stood out to me the most, once you got through the maze of the entry, was the connection to the backyard,” she says. While Boyer appreciated the sliding glass doors and transom windows at the rear of the house, the architect knew the indoor/outdoor connection could be even stronger. As it was, a solid wall down the center of the living spaces segmented the backyard views and hindered circulation. The mix of finishes from different eras—including a cottage-style pink-and-blue kitchen—weren’t doing the classic midcentury any favors. With the help of contractor @hammerandhandbuilds, the team extended the roof to create a generous covered patio area, accessed by a 23-foot-long glass door that slides into the wall for a seamless indoor/outdoor flow. New skylights in the roofing of the covered patio only emphasize the feeling of being outdoors. Our latest print issue drops on September 15th! In anticipation, we’re revisiting the awe-inspiring home that graced the cover of our September/October 2020 issue—and also claimed Runner-Up and Community Pick for best bathroom in the 2020 Dwell Design Awards.
Square House by New York City architecture studio @levenbetts is surely more sanctuary than ruin, but it walks a beautiful line between the two. For the owners, the guesthouse was about designing a vestige 500 years into the future and working backward to a functional home. Several years of dialogue—steered by that idea of design from the future—led to a quietly monolithic concrete box set in a contemplative landscape of rocks and moss. The connection to the outdoors is one of the home’s most astounding characteristics. Although it reads as a single story, the floor level rises and lowers with the site’s topography, intentionally altering your perspective as you progress through the house. “When you’re in the sunken living room, you’re lower than the ground plane and you see nature at a very different scale,” says Stella Betts, cofounder of Levenbetts. “It’s an idea of porosity, or being out in nature and then entering every room in the house from wherever.” Take the full tour of Square House when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

This home is so energy efficient that the family living in it, a young couple and their two children, required no additional heating last winter. To build in Barcelona’s L’Ametlla del Vallès, the couple partnered with local architects @slowstudio.es, a firm renowned for designing and constructing houses with reduced energy consumption. "We decided to allocate a main part of the budget to the passive functioning of the house, investing in materials that would provide us with environmental quality and energy efficiency," says Jade Serra (@jade_slowstudio), partner and cofounder of the firm. “In this case, we worked with a thermal buffer: the patio greenhouse.” Separating the bedrooms from the common spaces, a glass-covered courtyard runs through the center of the home and creates a greenhouse effect, mediating the 1,340-square-foot home’s climate. “The result is an economical, natural system that is as—or more—efficient than controlled mechanical ventilation."
